ime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1165–after 1234":"about 1165–after 1234","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","1190–1279":"1190–1279","1190–1287":"1190–1287","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1145–Female":"1145–Deceased","1190":"1190","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","Abt 1165":"about 1165","1287":"1287","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","after 1234":"after 1234","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Firm and resolute’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert II de Neufbourg, Seigneur de Livarot was born about 1165, in France, his father, Raoul de Neufbourg, Baron d’Asnebec, was 27 and his mother, Amaurie Paynel, was 22. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Isabeau Crespin, Dame de Livarot. He died after 1234."},"et":{"Abt 1165–after 1234":"umbes 1165–pärast 1234","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1190–1279":"1190–1279","1190–1287":"1190–1287","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1190":"1190","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","1287":"1287","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","after 1234":"pärast 1234","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1165–after 1234":"noin 1165–1234 jälkeen","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1190–1279":"1190–1279","1190–1287":"1190–1287","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","Abt 1165":"noin 1165","1287":"1287","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","after 1234":"1234 jälkeen","Abt 1190":"noin 1190","Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1165–after 1234":"environ 1165–après 1234","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1175–Female":"1175–Décédée","1